entries.meaning: Tanning liquor, an aqueous extract of vegetable matter (tanbark, sumac, etc.) in a tanning vat used to tan leather.
An oozing, gentle flowing, or seepage, as of water through sand or earth.

verbs.description: ooze (third-person singular simple present oozes, present participle oozing, simple past and past participle oozed)

entries.meaning: (intransitive, sometimes figurative) To be secreted or slowly leak.
examples: I promised him I would keep silence, but the story gradually oozed out, and the Cronsons left the country.

entries.meaning: (transitive, figuratively) To give off a strong sense of (something); to exude.

description: From Middle English wose, from Old English wāse (“mud, mire”), from Proto-West Germanic [Term?], from Proto-Germanic *waisǭ (compare Dutch waas (“haze, mist; bloom”), (obsolete) German Wasen (“turf, sod”), Old Norse veisa (“slime, stagnant pool”)), from Proto-Indo-European *weys- (“to flow”) (compare Sanskrit विष्यति (viṣyati, “flow, let loose”)). More at virus.

entries.meaning: Soft mud, slime, or shells especially in the bed of a river or estuary.
(oceanography) A pelagic marine sediment containing a significant amount of the microscopic remains of either calcareous or siliceous planktonic debris organisms.
A piece of soft, wet, pliable ground.
